content.description: Two short toprope problems can be climbed from anchors at the top. Figuring out how to get to the anchors can be the crux! Trending left is 10+, right is 10-. Go to it.
content.location: Just right of the 'Bear Grunts' crack.

content.description: One of the first eye catching lines as you walk the Rockband is this right facing dihedral. Leaning slightly to the right, it does not look as sweet as it climbs. May feel sandbagged until you've done a couple of laps and gotten it dialed. This thing sucks up nuts.
content.protection: Standard rack to 2", emphasis on smaller nuts. Offset nuts sing.
content.location: The first full dihedral you come to after cresting the approach hill. Gear belay, or extend a looong sling from tree. Rap from 'Dog Days' or walk off climbers right.

content.description:
The line looks better from the ground thn it plays out, although it is fun. Pro is iffy at the top, and because it is not climbed often enough, as with much of the rock on Eagle Peak, it can be dirty.

Start as for 'Dogleg'; where you move up in the first (lefthand) crack, continue right into the more obvious declivity, towards the arete. Then up the right hand crack, to where the crack thins out and this turns into a poorly protected face climb.
content.protection: Standard rack to 3". Tricams and small cams for the top. Gear belay, or sling a tree.
content.location: Same start as Dogleg. Rap from 'Dog Days' or walk off climbers right.

content.description: Fun vert route with good holds to the top arete/lip. Traverse to the pointed top of the boulder.
content.location: Look for the tall, vertical diamond face as you walk down into more of the routes in Eagle Peak, after you top the hill. Faces southeast.

content.description:
Spawning from the

Red Dawn

dihedral is this subtle left-slanting crack. The crux comes about halfway up as one must work around vegetation on steep rock. Good fingerlocks lie just above. There is a chained tree at the top that can be used for toprope and descent.
content.location:
Left-slanting crack spawning out the left side of the

Red Dawn

dihedral.

content.description: One of those "I wish it were longer" routes. An obvious left facing, left leaning, red dihedral. Pro is great at the crux, a good line for those just breaking into the grade. It is somewhat easier (5.9+?) if you use the large flake.
content.location: Look for the very red, very obvious left facing dihedral. Rap the route.

content.description: Sit start on the overhang with most of your weight on a left hand jug with good feet, and a right hand mono pocket. Immediately pull up with your right hand to a jug (Crux) and continue up obvious holds to a fun topout.
content.location: 15 Foot boulder right in front of the boulder with the huge roof below the Peapod and Right area

content.description: Somewhat contrived, but hey, it's a toprope, eh? Start as for Duckpins, then step left onto the steep face and up to the anchor for Lawn Bowling. Fun to play on.
content.location: Same as Duckpins.

content.description: A deservedly popular climb. Climb up the near vertical hand crack to and over the bulge (crux). The angle eases to the top where there is a 2 bolt anchor. Some find this harder than the grade, a good line to practice gear placement and creative climbing techniques.
content.location: In the approximate center of the rock band, look for the alcove with a bolted face (hard to see the rusty bolts) between 2 corner cracks (Peapod on the right and Peabody on the left). The bulge on Peapod is easily recognized.

content.description: A broken line which would be much better but for he fact that most of the climb is easy 5th on giant ledges. Fun is to be had playing on all the toprope options from the anchor. Starts in an uncomfortable bush stance.
content.protection: Standard rack to 5". Easily toproped from chains above the line.
content.location: To the right of the 'bowling ball' lines, look for the cool looking overhung section with a wide crack leading up it's right hand edge. Chain anchor at the top, or you can walk off climbers right.

content.description: Sit start around the arete on the lowest obvious hold then pull a few jugs on the arete. Move left on to the overhang, stand up and use the obvious undercling to gain a 2 finger downpull on the arete, lockoff to a large jug a few feet below the top of the boulder. Awesome line with awesome moves!
content.location: look for a slightly overhanging boulder leaning against a few other large boulders as you walk down on the outer side of the boulder field. immediately to the right of Sexy Mexican Jesus.

content.description: Look for the very eye catching triangle hole in the rock, about 5' off the ground. The line travels past this, through six bolts to a bolted anchor. Well protected, good intro to sport in the area.
content.location: See the triangle hole? See the 6 bolts above it? You're there.

climbs.name: Foxtrot
climbs.fa: Ricky Miller, Jim Smith, Ed Speer (June 2007)

content.description: This route has a one-move-wonder getting off the ground followed by trivial climbing up a brush-filled gully. There is a chained tree at the top that can be used for toprope and descent.
content.location:
Left-slanting brush-filled gully about 10 feet to the right of

California Dreaming

.

content.description: Another great line by Travis Klawin & Co. Six older bolts ascend this lovely orange arete. The anchors on top have been more recently replaced and are in better shape than the bolts and hangers of the climb itself.
content.location: Arete to the right of Peapod.

content.description: Ascend the crack which leaves the alcove to the right of Bowling Ball Right. Trends up and right into the corner.
content.location: Leaves the alcove to the right behind the large bolder hiding the 'Bowling' routes from below. Lower from Lawn Bowling, or BBR, or walk off climbers right.

content.description: Start as for baby dog after 10' cut right and up to where the crack branches. Take the first left, the crack continues trending up right. Gear can be intermittent, but good.
content.protection: Standard sack to 2". Doubles in fingers.
content.location: Same start as Baby Dog. Gear belay, rap from Dog Days or walk off climbers right.

climbs.name: Dog Days
climbs.fa: Ricky Miller, Miichael and Sean Simpson

content.description: A sandbagged 5.4, might be 5.4d!  Find the thin crack/groove on the low angle bulge. Bolted ancor at the top.
content.location: To the right of Bowling.

climbs.name: California Dreaming
climbs.fa: Ricky Miller, Michael Simpson, Sean Simpson (Sept 2005)

content.description:
The bottom half of this route ascends a shallow right-facing corner that has the approximate outline of the west coast of California. The top of the corner presents a nasty crux encounter on flaky rock. Past this, jam through a small roof and continue up easy ledges to the top of the wall.

To descend, walk to the right and rappel from the chained tree at the top of

Second Wind

and

Foxtrot

.
content.location:
This is the shallow right-facing corner approximately 30 feet left of the obvious left-facing red dihedral known as

Red Dawn.

content.description: An entertaining line, with little pro. The hard moves are low, but really unprotected, with a ground fall potential if you miss the move. Can be somewhat dirty as it is not often climbed. Definitely rates an 'R' rating!
content.protection: Rack to 3", tricams for pockets and small cams for thin intermittent cracks if you can find them. Gear belay takes 1-3"
content.location: Start between the 2 Bowling Ball lines on a bulging face. Get a spot, as the crux is right off the ground and hard to spot. Bushes hide the start. Walk off climbers right or rap Bowling Ball Right.

content.description:
Climb the wide smooth crack using the edges and ledges. Eases at the large ledge then finishes up a short fun wall. Chains at the top.

Anchors equipped with mussy hooks for lowering by ASCA
content.location: Behind the large boulder find an alcove, Bowling Ball Right ascends the right side up through the wide, almost chimney, crack. Easily protected with various sizes of gear.

content.description: A fun line a and good introduction to the rockband. More of a struggle if you stay in the crack, the easiest way up is climbing the right hand face and using the crack for pro. Gear anchor (2-3").
content.location: Starts in a pod right off the ground, quickly narrows to fists/hands with good gear deeper in the crack. Need to do a little bushwacking to get to the start if it has not been climbed recently. Gear belay, walk off to climbers right or rap Mink Stink or Bowling Ball Right.

content.description:
The very first line as you crest the hill and reach the Rockband proper is a short, hard to see sport route. Look for the little roof, and try and spot the bolts above and below the bulge. Easier for those with reach, a tough intro to the 'band'.

Walk up the third class ramp to a ledge directly under the small roof, clipping 2 bolts, find the hidden, hard to figure out pockets, clip the bolt over the lip, away you go. Easier to pink point for those without ape arms!
content.location: Find the triangle hole of 'Holy Trinity', move right about 50'. Look up. The bolts start higher than you think.

content.description: Climb the block filled gulley/crack up and to the left.
content.location: 10' to the right of Eruption. Rap from 'Eruption' anchor or the tree above 'King Pin'.

content.description: Low sit start matched on a pinch/crimp with opposing foot, pull to a good edge. Route seems fairly lowball but has a fun topout and makes for a good warmup.
content.location: One of the first few boulders in Eagle Peak as you hike to the top of the hill on the approach. The line is on the west side of the boulder (facing the Eagle Peak rock band). Route is seasonal, as it is under snow until around August.

content.description: Crux? It's 5.4. A  little dirty from lack of climbing, but low exposure and easy pro make it a good intro to the rockband for newer climbers.
content.location: 20'+ to the right of the 'Bowling' alcove, look for the shallow groove with a crack in the back. There are no anchors at the top, either walk off to climbers right or rap from 'Dog Days'.
